ernative approaches to these issues based on Darwinian and associated biological post-Darwinian ideas. Their concerns included the Greek “race” or nation, its culture, language and identity; also politics and gender equality. Zarimis’s monograph devotes considerable space to Xenopoulos (1867-1951), notable novelist, journalist and playwright.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2022) 0aEvolution (Biology) in literature. 0aGreek literature, Moderny19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aGreek literature, Moderny20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aLiterature and science. 0aNatural selectionxPhilosophy. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh  aEarly 20th century, Gender, Identity, Intellectual life, Literature, Racism.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCentral European University Press eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311078054340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9789633860786423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9789633860786/original  a978-3-11-078054-3  Central European University Press eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK